metadata.name: Oscillators #249
metadata.description:
Click anywhere on the oscillator to play/pause.

3 Rules of Oscillators:
RULE 1, Oscillators should be viewed on Desktop (this is due to the way an oscillator is formed, it requires the display density of the device to be 2 pixels).
RULE 2, Oscillators should be viewed live and not as static images.
RULE 3, Oscillators should be run with the sound on.

Press "S" to Save a version of the Canvas (must be in fullscreen mode)

You are in a dark cave in the Johto region, the year is 1999...

Two synthesizers play a graceful melody atop the shimmering sound of a french horn. A cello provides a deep and haunting counterpoint.

Created with Tone.js and p5js.

Thank you to https://github.com/nbrosowsky/tonejs-instruments for the french horn and cello samples.

metadata.name: CHAOTIC UNIVERSE #28
metadata.description:
Many people today may find wonder what exactly is happening to us as we orbit and move around our planet. Some might assume that there’s not much in the way of a reason, others might assume that humans are just being lulled into complacency by having their every need met and be self-absorbed in technology. Or maybe those assumptions are wrong, but for those who know about something called Chaos Theory, it is possible - at least in theory - that we are living in the very beginning moments of a process of change which will pop up from nowhere to take over everything as time goes on.

Some would call it a surprise, but I don’t think a surprise is the right word. In fact, I think that it’s closer to bad luck than anything else. Those of us who know about Chaos Theory know that it’s even possible for a small change at the beginning of the universe to result in the formation of vastly different universes and some where we humans don’t even exist.

Now, this is not something like one person acting differently or changes in other people around that one person. It’s not the butterfly effect. It’s more like there were two people and it was 50-50 to either one of them doing something and then, suddenly, one of those people wasn’t there. How would the other person react? Would they take away a piece of food, or maybe that person wouldn’t have said a particular word at a particular time? In either case, even if it was a tiny tiny difference - I mean, who knows what someone did in the past to make this happen - there would be no way for us to know now that that tiny change decided what kind of universe we live in now and what our lives will be like tomorrow.

How would you feel? Would you think it was bad luck or good luck, or something else? Chances are, you’re going to feel the same way. And don’t think I don’t know what you are thinking of doing if the world was to end and there’d be nobody around but you.

Of course there are people who may have thought about doing something when they came across this article. Maybe people will assume that I am crazy for making these claims - which is fine as long as people assume that I am crazy in general. When things like this happen to us all at once, it is really hard for us to make sense of it all.

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #82
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

metadata.name: Asterium #297
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: Udnē #541
metadata.description:
Udnē is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022.

Udnē is a collection of asymmetric textural compositions. It's a search for creating harmonies and disharmonies by combining 3 colors with 3 unsynchronized mathematical equations. Udnē explores the beauty within triadic compositions while attempting to integrate two contrasting textures by forming instances of non-figurative scenes. The collection is a reflection of integrated and contrasting textures in micro and macro scale that we see in our everyday life environment.

You can press 's' in liveMode to save as 1000x1000px .png.

In liveMode, add '&density=7’ to the end of the URL to render at high resolution (7000x7000px). You can use 5, 7 or 10 for different resolutions. It will automatically download when the rendering is finished. 

Some compositions might take longer to render in low-performance computers. Please be patient and enjoy the process!

As a rare probability there is an intentionally kept glitch.

Made with p5js.
@distcollective, November 2022

metadata.name: Poem Of Atoms #11
metadata.description:
There is a force in the universe that binds everything together
It's a electronic web that connects everything in a delicate balance. 
Some call it fate. But few know the truth.
They are the lifeblood of our society, and they are what keep us moving forward. We are constantly surrounded by them, and they are always changing. It's not a force, it's an orbit. And the dots are the energy sources.

Made with P5js
